3. Description of the variables used in the analysis¶

a. Median house Value: The median house value in this dataset is our dependent variable, represents the median value of houses in a given area. the range of the median house value is $485,002 which can be calculated by subtracting the minimum number from the maximum number, which are values we can find in the exploration table above when we used the "Describe" Function. Minimum number- 14999, Maximum value- 500001. this variable gives us insight about the affordability of houses; showing where more expensive houses are located to where more affordable housing are.¶

b. Median Income: This represents the median household income in a given area. the median income ranges from minimum number of 0.5 to maximum number of 15.0, where these values represent minimum range as lower income areas and maximum range as the higher income areas. the median income value correlates with the housing value, because areas with higher median income have higher housing prices and areas with lower income have more affordable housing prices¶

c. Population: This Independent variable represents the total number of people residing in an area in the dataset. It ranges from minimum number of 3.0 to a maximum number of 35682.0. In region with more population, the housing demand might be greater and areas with lower population will also have lower housing demands.¶

d. Number of Households: This variable represents the total number of household that lives in a housing unit in a particular area. it helps us to provide insights on the housing market size. It ranges from a minimum number of 1.0 to a maximum number of 6082.0. this particular variable has a strong relationship with other housing variables like the total_rooms, total_bedrooms and median house value because more households could indicate a more active housing market.¶

Defining the model¶

In [14]:
## Importing the necessay library needed to define the model
from sklearn import linear_model
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, mean_absolute_error


## Creating a linear regression object
model = linear_model.LinearRegression()

Training the model¶

In [15]:
## Training the model for median income vs median house value (Fit)
model.fit(X=train[["median_income"]], y=train[["median_house_value"]])

## Intercept of the model
intercept_i = model.intercept_
print("intercept:",intercept_i)

## Slope of the model
slope_i = model.coef_[0]
print("slope:",slope_i)

## Prediction of model
y=train[["median_house_value"]]
y_predict_i = model.predict(X=train[["median_income"]])

## Calculating the mean squared error
mse_i = mean_squared_error(y,y_predict_i)
print("MSE:",mse_i)

## calculating the mean absolute error
mae_i = mean_absolute_error(y,y_predict_i)
print("MAE:",mae_i)

## mse for test set
y=test[["median_house_value"]]
y_predict_ii = model.predict(X=test[["median_income"]])
mse_ii = mean_squared_error(y,y_predict_ii)
print("MSE on test set:",mse_ii)

## mae for test set
mae_ii = mean_absolute_error(y,y_predict_ii)
print("MAE on test set:",mae_ii)

Regression line on each models¶

1. Regression graphs on trained sets¶

In [19]:
def plot_model_fixed(train, x_col, y_col, y_pred, intercept, slope, mse, mae, title):
   plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))
   plt.scatter(train[x_col], train[y_col], color="blue", label="Actual Data")
   plt.plot(train[x_col], y_pred, color="red", label=f"Fitted Line: y={slope[0]:.2f}x + {intercept:.2f}")
   plt.title(title)
   plt.xlabel(x_col)
   plt.ylabel(y_col)
   plt.legend()

   # Add text box with model parameters
   textstr = f'Intercept: {intercept:.2f}\nSlope: {slope[0]:.2f}\nMSE: {mse:.2f}\nMAE: {mae:.2f}'
   plt.gca().text(0.05, 0.95, textstr, transform=plt.gca().transAxes, fontsize=12,
                  verticalalignment='top', bbox=dict(boxstyle='round,pad=0.5', edgecolor='black', facecolor='lightgrey'))
   
   plt.show()

# Plot for Median House Value vs. Median Income
plot_model_fixed(train, "median_income", "median_house_value", y_predict_i, intercept_i[0], slope_i, mse_i, mae_i, "Median House Value vs. Median Income")

# Plot for Median House Value vs. Population
plot_model_fixed(train, "population", "median_house_value", y_predict_p, intercept_p[0], slope_p, mse_p, mae_p, "Median House Value vs. Population")

# Plot for Median House Value vs. Number of Households
plot_model_fixed(train, "households", "median_house_value", y_predict_h, intercept_h[0], slope_h, mse_h, mae_h, "Median House Value vs. Number of Households")

Conclusion¶

The goal of this report is to dive into the relationship between the several housing factors in this use case and how they play different roles in affecting the housing market. in this report. we trained three different linear regression models on their train and test dataset. the variables present in this linear regression model were¶

a. Median house value- which is a dependent variable because it depends on the other housing factors¶

b. Median income- Independent variable¶

c. Population- Independent variable¶

d. Number of households- Independent variable.¶

Goodness of Fit:The term goodness-of-fit refers to a statistical test that determines how well sample data fits a distribution from a population with a normal distribution. Put simply, it hypothesizes whether a sample is skewed or represents the data you would expect to find in the actual population.(https://www.investopedia.com/terms/g/goodness-of-fit.) Looking at their goodness of fit, the Mean squared value (MSE) represents the average difference squared of the actual value minus the predicted value. so a lower MSE indicates a better fit.¶

Also, the Mean Absolute error (MAE) represents the average absolute difference between the actual and predicted values and in this case the lower values are betetr than the higher values. in this case looking at the goodness of fit, the best model is the Median income,the normal model which is pretty moderate is the number of households, and the population model is the weakest out of all these models.¶
